								<div class="title" id="post-title-4228753">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/bibliolatry" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3534136); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3534136&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252598" alt="bibliolatry" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3534136)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/bibliolatry" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3534136); return false;" >bibliolatry</a></span> <span class="odate time_1556121445 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">24 Apr 2019 15:57</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4228753">
									

<p>One of the major reasons I don't like the GOC as an organization is their coalition structure. So you got all 108 of these different groups, and that's what causes all of the politics and voting blocs you see in this tale. But this is compounded: in addition to the Council of 108 politics, each individual member organization has it's OWN command structure, with even more voting blocs. This completely abstracts what any of these groups want. In the case of the <em>Nornir</em>, they probably have some dudes in there who personally don't like the Foundation, and they have some vague and twisty justifications for this in regards to their mission. They form a voting bloc to make The Speaker the one to sit at the table for this, probably on a technical minority, and there you have it.</p>

							</div>

								
